{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775896085217,"sessionID":"ses_2845c53fbffePPAJ9umtY57fu2","part":{"id":"prt_d7ba7c09a001uzN0ZTmpMsiCbx","messageID":"msg_d7ba79c89001QpIimtBbtui87X","sessionID":"ses_2845c53fbffePPAJ9umtY57fu2","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_6466db447fc14390a6755484","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_alibaba-cn-qwen3.6-plus_20260410T073331Z/deployment/design-e2e.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_alibaba-cn-qwen3.6-plus_20260410T073331Z/deployment/design-e2e.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-041: E2E 集成测试 — Design\n2: \n3: ## 1. Architecture\n4: \n5: ### 1.1 Purpose\n6: \n7: This AR covers end-to-end integration tests for the AgentCube system, validating the full request lifecycle across all four binaries (workloadmanager, router, agentd, picod) running in a real Kind Kubernetes cluster. Tests exercise CRD creation, sandbox lifecycle, reverse proxy routing, JWT authentication, session store synchronization, and idle cleanup.\n8: \n9: ### 1.2 Scope\n10: \n11: | Component | Coverage | Test Type |\n12: |-----------|----------|-----------|\n13: | `test/e2e/` | Full system E2E | Kind cluster, real binaries, real CRDs |\n14: | `test/e2e/framework/` | Test framework utilities | Cluster setup, client helpers, assertions |\n15: | `test/e2e/suites/` | Test scenario groups | Sandbox lifecycle, proxy, auth, cleanup |\n16: | `test/e2e/fixtures/` | CRD YAML fixtures | AgentRuntime, CodeInterpreter manifests |\n17: | `Makefile` | `e2e`, `e2e-clean` targets | CI integration |\n18: \n19: ### 1.3 System Context\n20: \n21: ```\n22: ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n23: │                          Kind Cluster                                    │\n24: │                                                                          │\n25: │  ┌──────────────┐    ┌──────────────────┐    ┌──────────────────────┐  │\n26: │  │  workloadmgr │───▶│  K8s API Server  │◀───│     agentd            │  │\n27: │  │  (Gin HTTP)  │    │  (etcd)          │    │  (controller-runtime) │  │\n28: │  └──────┬───────┘    └────────┬─────────┘    └──────────────────────┘  │\n29: │         │                     │                                         │\n30: │         │              ┌──────▼──────────┐                              │\n31: │         │              │   Sandbox Pods   │◀──── picod (sidecar)        │\n32: │         │              │  (code-interp /  │                              │\n33: │         │              │   agent-runtime) │                              │\n34: │         │              └──────┬───────────┘                              │\n35: │         │                     │                                          │\n36: │  ┌──────▼───────┐    ┌────────▼─────────┐    ┌──────────────────────┐  │\n37: │  │    router    │───▶│  Session Store   │    │   Informers/Watchers │  │\n38: │  │  (Gin proxy) │    │  (Redis/Valkey)  │    │   (client-go)        │  │\n39: │  └──────────────┘    └──────────────────┘    └──────────────────────┘  │\n40: │                                                                          │\n41: └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n42:          ▲\n43:          │  HTTP requests (curl / Go http.Client)\n44:          │\n45:   ┌──────┴──────┐\n46:   │  E2E Test   │\n47:   │  Runner     │\n48:   └─────────────┘\n49: ```\n50: \n51: ### 1.4 Design Principles\n52: \n53: - **Real cluster, real binaries**: Tests run against actual binaries deployed in Kind, not mocks.\n54: - **CRD-first**: All sandbox operations go through CRD creation/deletion, mirroring production.\n55: - **Idempotent**: Each test creates uniquely named resources (UUID-suffixed) and cleans up on exit.\n56: - **Fail-fast with diagnostics**: On failure, capture pod logs, events, and store state before teardown.\n57: - **Deterministic timeouts**: All waits use explicit deadlines; no infinite blocks.\n58: - **Sequential by default**: Tests run sequentially to avoid resource contention; parallel groups where safe.\n59: \n60: ### 1.5 Test Framework Structure\n61: \n62: ```\n63: test/e2e/\n64: ├── run_e2e.sh                          # Entry script: build, load images, deploy, run tests\n65: ├── main.go                             # Go test entry point (TestMain with setup/teardown)\n66: ├── framework/\n67: │   ├── cluster.go                      # Kind cluster lifecycle (create, delete, kubeconfig)\n68: │   ├── deploy.go                       # Helm install, binary image loading, CRD apply\n69: │   ├── clients.go                      # K8s clientset, dynamic client, REST client builders\n70: │   ├── wait.go                         # Polling helpers (wait for pod ready, CR status, HTTP)\n71: │   ├── http.go                         # HTTP client with retry, port-forward helpers\n72: │   ├── cleanup.go                      # Resource cleanup tracker (defer-based)\n73: │   └── assertions.go                   # Custom assert helpers (Eventually, Consistently)\n74: ├── suites/\n75: │   ├── sandbox_lifecycle/\n76: │   │   ├── suite_test.go               # Ginkgo suite bootstrap\n77: │   │   ├── create_test.go              # Create AgentRuntime / CodeInterpreter sandboxes\n78: │   │   ├── status_test.go              # Verify CR status transitions (pending → running)\n79: │   │   └── delete_test.go              # Delete sandbox, verify cleanup\n80: │   ├── proxy/\n81: │   │   ├── suite_test.go\n82: │   │   ├── routing_test.go             # Router forwards to correct sandbox pod\n83: │   │   ├── session_test.go             # Session ID propagation, last-activity updates\n84: │   │   └── multi_endpoint_test.go      # Multiple entry points, path-based routing\n85: │   ├── auth/\n86: │   │   ├── suite_test.go\n87: │   │   ├── jwt_test.go                 # JWT generation, validation, expiry\n88: │   │   └── rbac_test.go                # ServiceAccount token, namespace isolation\n89: │   ├── store/\n90: │   │   ├── suite_test.go\n91: │   │   └── sync_test.go                # Session store consistency across components\n92: │   └── agentd/\n93: │       ├── suite_test.go\n94: │       └── idle_cleanup_test.go        # Idle timeout triggers sandbox deletion\n95: └── fixtures/\n96:     ├── agentruntime.yaml               # Minimal AgentRuntime CR for testing\n97:     ├── codeinterpreter.yaml            # Minimal CodeInterpreter CR for testing\n98:     ├── codeinterpreter-warmpool.yaml   # CodeInterpreter with warmPoolSize > 0\n99:     └── codeinterpreter-picod-auth.yaml # CodeInterpreter with authMode: picod\n100: ```\n101: \n102: ### 1.6 Technology Choices\n103: \n104: | Component | Choice | Rationale |\n105: |-----------|--------|-----------|\n106: | Test framework | **Ginkgo + Gomega** | BDD-style, built-in `Eventually`/`Consistently` for async assertions, widely used in K8s ecosystem |\n107: | Cluster | **Kind v0.30.0** | Matches CI workflow, fast startup, Docker-based |\n108: | Image loading | `kind load docker-image` | Pre-built images loaded into cluster nodes |\n109: | Deployment | **Helm** (`helm install`) | Same chart as production, tests chart correctness too |\n110: | Port-forward | `kubectl port-forward` | Access in-cluster services from test runner |\n111: | HTTP client | Go `net/http` + retry | Direct HTTP calls to workloadmanager and router |\n112: \n113: ## 2. Data Structures\n114: \n115: ### 2.1 Test Environment Config\n116: \n117: ```go\n118: type TestEnv struct {\n119:     KubeConfigPath   string        // Path to Kind kubeconfig\n120:     ClusterName      string        // Kind cluster name (default: agentcube-e2e)\n121:     Namespace        string        // Test namespace (auto-generated with UUID suffix)\n122:     Registry         string        // Docker registry for images\n123:     ImageTag         string        // Image tag (default: e2e-test)\n124:     WorkloadMgrURL   string        // workloadmanager service URL (after port-forward)\n125:     RouterURL        string        // router service URL (after port-forward)\n126:     StoreType        string        // \"redis\" or \"valkey\"\n127:     EnableAuth       bool          // Whether auth is enabled in deployment\n128: }\n129: ```\n130: \n131: ### 2.2 Test Fixture Types\n132: \n133: ```go\n134: type SandboxFixture struct {\n135:     Name         string            // CR name (unique per test)\n136:     Namespace    string            // Target namespace\n137:     Kind         string            // \"AgentRuntime\" or \"CodeInterpreter\"\n138:     Image        string            // Container image for sandbox pod\n139:     Ports        []TargetPort      // Exposed ports\n140:     AuthMode     string            // \"picod\" or \"none\"\n141:     WarmPoolSize *int32            // Optional warm pool configuration\n142:     Labels       map[string]string // Additional labels\n143: }\n144: \n145: type SandboxResult struct {\n146:     SessionID   string        // Returned session ID\n147:     SandboxID   string        // K8s UID of created sandbox\n148:     SandboxName string        // Generated sandbox name\n149:     EntryPoints []EntryPoint  // Resolved entry points\n150:     PodIP       string        // Pod IP address\n151:     Status      string        // Final status (\"running\", \"failed\", etc.)\n152: }\n153: ```\n154: \n155: ### 2.3 Cleanup Tracker\n156: \n157: ```go\n158: type CleanupTracker struct {\n159:     mu       sync.Mutex\n160:     resources []cleanupFunc // Functions to call during teardown\n161: }\n162: \n163: type cleanupFunc struct {\n164:     name string\n165:     fn   func() error\n166: }\n167: \n168: // Usage:\n169: // ct := NewCleanupTracker()\n170: // defer ct.Cleanup()\n171: // ct.Add(\"delete-sandbox\", func() error { return client.Delete(...) })\n172: ```\n173: \n174: ### 2.4 Assertion Helpers (Gomega matchers)\n175: \n176: ```go\n177: // Custom matchers\n178: func BeRunningStatus() types.GomegaMatcher\n179: func HaveSessionID() types.GomegaMatcher\n180: func HaveEntryPointWithPath(path string) types.GomegaMatcher\n181: func MatchHTTPStatus(code int) types.GomegaMatcher\n182: ```\n183: \n184: ## 3. API Contracts\n185: \n186: ### 3.1 Workload Manager Endpoints (tested via E2E)\n187: \n188: | Method | Path | Request Body | Success Response | Error Codes |\n189: |--------|------|-------------|------------------|-------------|\n190: | POST | `/v1/agent-runtime` | `{\"kind\":\"AgentRuntime\",\"name\":\"<cr-name>\",\"namespace\":\"<ns>\"}` | `200 {sessionId, sandboxId, sandboxName, entryPoints}` | 400 (invalid), 404 (CR not found), 500 (internal) |\n191: | POST | `/v1/code-interpreter` | `{\"kind\":\"CodeInterpreter\",\"name\":\"<cr-name>\",\"namespace\":\"<ns>\"}` | `200 {sessionId, sandboxId, sandboxName, entryPoints}` | 400, 404, 500 |\n192: | DELETE | `/v1/sessions/{sessionId}` | — | `200 {\"message\":\"session deleted\"}` | 404 (not found), 500 |\n193: \n194: ### 3.2 Router Endpoints (tested via E2E)\n195: \n196: | Method | Path | Headers | Behavior |\n197: |--------|------|---------|----------|\n198: | ANY | `/invoke/agent-runtime/{namespace}/{name}/*path` | `x-agentcube-session-id` (optional) | Resolves sandbox, proxies to pod, sets `x-agentcube-session-id` response header |\n199: | ANY | `/invoke/code-interpreter/{namespace}/{name}/*path` | `x-agentcube-session-id` (optional) | Same as above for CodeInterpreter |\n200: \n201: ### 3.3 Expected E2E Flow\n202: \n203: ```\n204: 1. E2E test applies AgentRuntime/CodeInterpreter CR via kubectl\n205: 2. Test waits for CR to be recognized by informers (reconciler sync)\n206: 3. Test POSTs to workloadmanager /v1/agent-runtime or /v1/code-interpreter\n207: 4. workloadmanager creates Sandbox CR, watches for Running status\n208: 5. workloadmanager stores session in Redis, returns entry points\n209: 6. Test sends HTTP request to router /invoke/... endpoint\n210: 7. Router resolves session from store, generates JWT, proxies to sandbox pod\n211: 8. Sandbox pod (picod) responds; router forwards response back\n212: 9. Test verifies response headers, session ID, status code\n213: 10. Test deletes session, verifies cleanup\n214: ```\n215: \n216: ## 4. Error Handling\n217: \n218: ### 4.1 Test-Level Error Handling\n219: \n220: | Scenario | Handling Strategy |\n221: |----------|-------------------|\n222: | Kind cluster creation fails | Abort all tests, print `kind create cluster` logs |\n223: | Image load fails | Abort, show `docker build` and `kind load` output |\n224: | Helm install fails | Abort, show `helm install` stderr and `kubectl get events` |\n225: | Pod fails to start | Capture pod describe, logs, events; fail specific test |\n226: | HTTP request timeout | Retry up to 3 times with exponential backoff; fail with captured state |\n227: | CRD not recognized | Wait up to 30s for CRD establishment; fail if not ready |\n228: | Store connection refused | Check Redis/Valkey pod status; fail with diagnostics |\n229: \n230: ### 4.2 Per-Test Error Recovery\n231: \n232: ```go\n233: // Each test follows this pattern:\n234: It(\"creates a sandbox and proxies request\", func() {\n235:     // Setup\n236:     fixture := createFixture()\n237:     cleanup.Add(\"delete-cr\", func() error { return deleteCR(fixture) })\n238: \n239:     // Act\n240:     result, err := createSandbox(fixture)\n241:     Expect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n242: \n243:     // Verify\n244:     Eventually(func() error {\n245:         return verifySandboxRunning(result.SandboxName)\n246:     }, 2*time.Minute, 5*time.Second).Should(Succeed())\n247: \n248:     // Proxy test\n249:     resp, err := routerClient.Invoke(result.SessionID, \"/health\")\n250:     Expect(resp.StatusCode).To(Equal(200))\n251: \n252:     // Cleanup is deferred\n253: })\n254: ```\n255: \n256: ### 4.3 Diagnostic Collection on Failure\n257: \n258: ```go\n259: // Collected on test failure (Ginkgo AfterEach with Failed status):\n260: func CollectDiagnostics(namespace string) {\n261:     // kubectl get events -n <namespace>\n262:     // kubectl get pods -n <namespace> -o wide\n263:     // kubectl logs <workloadmanager-pod> -n <namespace>\n264:     // kubectl logs <router-pod> -n <namespace>\n265:     // kubectl logs <agentd-pod> -n <namespace>\n266:     // kubectl logs <sandbox-pod> -n <namespace>\n267:     // kubectl exec <redis-pod> -- redis-cli keys \"*\"\n268:     // Save to $ARTIFACTS_PATH/<test-name>/\n269: }\n270: ```\n271: \n272: ## 5. Testing Strategy\n273: \n274: ### 5.1 Test Suites\n275: \n276: #### Suite 1: Sandbox Lifecycle (`suites/sandbox_lifecycle/`)\n277: \n278: | Test ID | Name | Steps | Expected |\n279: |---------|------|-------|----------|\n280: | E2E-SL-01 | Create AgentRuntime sandbox | Apply AgentRuntime CR → POST /v1/agent-runtime → wait for Running | 200 response with valid sessionId, sandboxName, entryPoints |\n281: | E2E-SL-02 | Create CodeInterpreter sandbox | Apply CodeInterpreter CR → POST /v1/code-interpreter → wait for Running | 200 response with valid sessionId, entryPoints with port 8080 |\n282: | E2E-SL-03 | Create CodeInterpreter with warm pool | Apply CodeInterpreter (warmPoolSize=2) → POST /v1/code-interpreter | Creates SandboxClaim, returns session |\n283: | E2E-SL-04 | Create with picod auth mode | Apply CodeInterpreter (authMode: picod) → POST /v1/code-interpreter | Sandbox has PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY env var |\n284: | E2E-SL-05 | Duplicate session handling | Create sandbox → Create again with same CR name | Returns existing session or 409 |\n285: | E2E-SL-06 | Delete sandbox | Create sandbox → DELETE /v1/sessions/{sessionId} | 200 response, Sandbox CR deleted, store entry removed |\n286: | E2E-SL-07 | Delete non-existent session | DELETE /v1/sessions/{nonexistent-id} | 404 response |\n287: | E2E-SL-08 | Create with missing CR | POST /v1/agent-runtime with non-existent CR name | 404 response |\n288: | E2E-SL-09 | Create with invalid request | POST /v1/agent-runtime with empty body | 400 response |\n289: | E2E-SL-10 | Sandbox status transition | Create sandbox → poll CR status | Status transitions: pending → running within 2 minutes |\n290: \n291: #### Suite 2: Proxy Routing (`suites/proxy/`)\n292: \n293: | Test ID | Name | Steps | Expected |\n294: |---------|------|-------|----------|\n295: | E2E-PR-01 | Proxy to AgentRuntime | Create AgentRuntime sandbox → GET /invoke/agent-runtime/{ns}/{name}/health | 200, response from sandbox pod |\n296: | E2E-PR-02 | Proxy to CodeInterpreter | Create CodeInterpreter sandbox → GET /invoke/code-interpreter/{ns}/{name}/health | 200, response from sandbox pod |\n297: | E2E-PR-03 | Session ID propagation | Invoke sandbox → check response headers | `x-agentcube-session-id` header present and matches |\n298: | E2E-PR-04 | Path-based routing | Sandbox with multiple entry points → invoke different paths | Request routed to correct port based on path prefix |\n299: | E2E-PR-05 | Last-activity update | Invoke sandbox → check store | `lastActivityAt` updated in Redis |\n300: | E2E-PR-06 | On-demand sandbox creation | Invoke without session ID (no existing session) | Router creates sandbox via workloadmanager, returns proxied response |\n301: | E2E-PR-07 | Proxy with invalid session | Invoke with non-existent session ID | 404 response |\n302: | E2E-PR-08 | Proxy to unreachable sandbox | Create sandbox, kill pod → invoke | 502 or 504 response, not crash |\n303: | E2E-PR-09 | Header forwarding | Invoke sandbox → check forwarded headers on sandbox side | `X-Forwarded-For`, `X-Forwarded-Host`, `X-Forwarded-Proto` present |\n304: | E2E-PR-10 | Concurrent proxy requests | Send 10 concurrent requests to same sandbox | All succeed, no data race |\n305: \n306: #### Suite 3: Authentication (`suites/auth/`)\n307: \n308: | Test ID | Name | Steps | Expected |\n309: |---------|------|-------|----------|\n310: | E2E-AT-01 | JWT in proxy request | Create sandbox → invoke → check JWT in proxied request | JWT present with valid session_id claim |\n311: | E2E-AT-02 | PicoD auth validation | Create CodeInterpreter with picod auth → execute code via proxy | 200, code executes successfully |\n312: | E2E-AT-03 | Invalid JWT rejection | Send request with malformed JWT to picod | 401 from picod |\n313: | E2E-AT-04 | ServiceAccount token auth | Create sandbox with SA token in Authorization header | 200, sandbox created with user-scoped client |\n314: | E2E-AT-05 | Missing auth token | Create sandbox without Authorization header (auth enabled) | 401 response |\n315: \n316: #### Suite 4: Session Store (`suites/store/`)\n317: \n318: | Test ID | Name | Steps | Expected |\n319: |---------|------|-------|----------|\n320: | E2E-ST-01 | Store consistency after create | Create sandbox → query store directly | Session exists with correct sandboxId, entryPoints, status=running |\n321: | E2E-ST-02 | Store cleanup after delete | Delete session → query store | Session entry removed |\n322: | E2E-ST-03 | Reconciler sync to store | Modify CR externally → wait for reconcile | Store reflects CR status change |\n323: | E2E-ST-04 | Store survives pod restart | Restart workloadmanager → query store | Sessions persist (Redis-backed) |\n324: \n325: #### Suite 5: Agentd Idle Cleanup (`suites/agentd/`)\n326: \n327: | Test ID | Name | Steps | Expected |\n328: |---------|------|-------|----------|\n329: | E2E-AC-01 | Idle timeout triggers deletion | Create sandbox → wait without activity → check sandbox | Sandbox deleted after idle timeout |\n330: | E2E-AC-02 | Activity resets idle timer | Create sandbox → invoke (updates lastActivityAt) → wait | Sandbox NOT deleted (timer reset) |\n331: | E2E-AC-03 | Max session duration | Create sandbox with short TTL → wait | Sandbox deleted after max duration |\n332: \n333: ### 5.2 Test Execution Flow\n334: \n335: ```\n336: run_e2e.sh:\n337:   1. Build all Go binaries (make build)\n338:   2. Build Docker images (make docker)\n339:   3. Create Kind cluster (kind create cluster --name agentcube-e2e)\n340:   4. Load images into Kind (kind load docker-image ...)\n341:   5. Install Redis/Valkey (helm install redis ...)\n342:   6. Deploy AgentCube (helm install agentcube manifests/charts/base/)\n343:   7. Wait for all pods ready (kubectl wait --for=condition=Ready)\n344:   8. Run Go E2E tests (go test ./test/e2e/... -v -timeout 30m)\n345:   9. On failure: collect diagnostics to $ARTIFACTS_PATH\n346:   10. Clean up (make e2e-clean)\n347: ```\n348: \n349: ### 5.3 Makefile Targets\n350: \n351: ```makefile\n352: # Add to existing Makefile:\n353: \n354: .PHONY: e2e e2e-clean\n355: \n356: E2E_TIMEOUT ?= 30m\n357: E2E_ARTIFACTS ?= $(shell pwd)/e2e-logs\n358: \n359: e2e:\n360: \t$(Q)bash test/e2e/run_e2e.sh\n361: \n362: e2e-clean:\n363: \t$(Q)kind delete cluster --name agentcube-e2e 2>/dev/null || true\n364: \t$(Q)rm -rf $(E2E_ARTIFACTS)\n365: ```\n366: \n367: ### 5.4 Entry Script (`test/e2e/run_e2e.sh`)\n368: \n369: ```bash\n370: #!/usr/bin/env bash\n371: set -euo pipefail\n372: \n373: CLUSTER_NAME=\"agentcube-e2e\"\n374: REGISTRY=\"${REGISTRY:-agentcube}\"\n375: TAG=\"${TAG:-e2e-test}\"\n376: ARTIFACTS_PATH=\"${ARTIFACTS_PATH:-$(pwd)/e2e-logs}\"\n377: NAMESPACE=\"agentcube-e2e-$(date +%s)\"\n378: \n379: echo \"=== AgentCube E2E Tests ===\"\n380: echo \"Cluster: ${CLUSTER_NAME}\"\n381: echo \"Registry: ${REGISTRY}\"\n382: echo \"Tag: ${TAG}\"\n383: echo \"Artifacts: ${ARTIFACTS_PATH}\"\n384: \n385: # Step 1: Build images\n386: echo \"--- Building Docker images ---\"\n387: make docker TAG=\"${TAG}\" REGISTRY=\"${REGISTRY}\"\n388: \n389: # Step 2: Create Kind cluster\n390: echo \"--- Creating Kind cluster ---\"\n391: kind create cluster --name \"${CLUSTER_NAME}\" --wait 60s\n392: \n393: # Step 3: Load images\n394: echo \"--- Loading images into Kind ---\"\n395: for img in agentcube router picod; do\n396:   kind load docker-image \"${REGISTRY}/${img}:${TAG}\" --name \"${CLUSTER_NAME}\"\n397: done\n398: \n399: # Step 4: Deploy dependencies (Redis)\n400: echo \"--- Deploying Redis ---\"\n401: helm install redis bitnami/redis --set auth.enabled=false --wait\n402: \n403: # Step 5: Deploy AgentCube\n404: echo \"--- Deploying AgentCube ---\"\n405: helm install agentcube manifests/charts/base/ \\\n406:   --set image.registry=\"${REGISTRY}\" \\\n407:   --set image.tag=\"${TAG}\" \\\n408:   --set workloadmanager.store.type=\"redis\" \\\n409:   --set workloadmanager.store.redis.host=\"redis-master\" \\\n410:   --set router.store.type=\"redis\" \\\n411:   --set router.store.redis.host=\"redis-master\" \\\n412:   --namespace \"${NAMESPACE}\" --create-namespace --wait\n413: \n414: # Step 6: Wait for readiness\n415: echo \"--- Waiting for pods ---\"\n416: kubectl wait --for=condition=Ready pods --all -n \"${NAMESPACE}\" --timeout=120s\n417: \n418: # Step 7: Run E2E tests\n419: echo \"--- Running E2E tests ---\"\n420: export E2E_NAMESPACE=\"${NAMESPACE}\"\n421: export E2E_CLUSTER_NAME=\"${CLUSTER_NAME}\"\n422: export ARTIFACTS_PATH=\"${ARTIFACTS_PATH}\"\n423: \n424: go test ./test/e2e/... -v -timeout \"${E2E_TIMEOUT}\" \\\n425:   -ginkgo.v \\\n426:   -ginkgo.junit-report=\"${ARTIFACTS_PATH}/e2e-junit.xml\"\n427: \n428: echo \"=== E2E Tests Passed ===\"\n429: ```\n430: \n431: ### 5.5 Fixture Files\n432: \n433: #### `fixtures/agentruntime.yaml`\n434: \n435: ```yaml\n436: apiVersion: runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh/v1alpha1\n437: kind: AgentRuntime\n438: metadata:\n439:   name: test-agent-runtime\n440:   namespace: default\n441: spec:\n442:   ports:\n443:     - name: http\n444:       port: 8080\n445:       protocol: HTTP\n446:       pathPrefix: /\n447:   template:\n448:     labels:\n449:       app: test-agent\n450:     spec:\n451:       containers:\n452:         - name: agent\n453:           image: nginx:1.25-alpine\n454:           ports:\n455:             - containerPort: 8080\n456:           readinessProbe:\n457:             httpGet:\n458:               path: /\n459:               port: 8080\n460:             initialDelaySeconds: 2\n461:             periodSeconds: 5\n462:   sessionTimeout: 15m\n463:   maxSessionDuration: 1h\n464: ```\n465: \n466: #### `fixtures/codeinterpreter.yaml`\n467: \n468: ```yaml\n469: apiVersion: runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh/v1alpha1\n470: kind: CodeInterpreter\n471: metadata:\n472:   name: test-code-interpreter\n473:   namespace: default\n474: spec:\n475:   ports:\n476:     - name: http\n477:       port: 8080\n478:       protocol: HTTP\n479:       pathPrefix: /\n480:   template:\n481:     image: nginx:1.25-alpine\n482:     imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent\n483:     command: [\"nginx\", \"-g\", \"daemon off;\"]\n484:     resources:\n485:       requests:\n486:         cpu: 100m\n487:         memory: 128Mi\n488:       limits:\n489:         cpu: 500m\n490:         memory: 256Mi\n491:   sessionTimeout: 15m\n492:   maxSessionDuration: 1h\n493:   authMode: none\n494: ```\n495: \n496: #### `fixtures/codeinterpreter-warmpool.yaml`\n497: \n498: ```yaml\n499: apiVersion: runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh/v1alpha1\n500: kind: CodeInterpreter\n501: metadata:\n502:   name: test-code-interpreter-warmpool\n503:   namespace: default\n504: spec:\n505:   ports:\n506:     - name: http\n507:       port: 8080\n508:       protocol: HTTP\n509:       pathPrefix: /\n510:   template:\n511:     image: nginx:1.25-alpine\n512:     imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent\n513:   warmPoolSize: 2\n514:   sessionTimeout: 15m\n515:   maxSessionDuration: 1h\n516:   authMode: none\n517: ```\n518: \n519: ### 5.6 CI Integration\n520: \n521: The existing `.github/workflows/e2e.yml` already defines the Kind cluster setup and calls `make e2e`. The implementation must ensure:\n522: \n523: 1. `make e2e` invokes `test/e2e/run_e2e.sh`\n524: 2. `make e2e-clean` runs on `always()` (already configured)\n525: 3. Logs are uploaded to `$ARTIFACTS_PATH` on failure (already configured)\n526: 4. Test timeout fits within GitHub Actions job timeout (default 360 minutes)\n527: \n528: ### 5.7 Test Image Strategy\n529: \n530: For E2E tests, sandbox pods use `nginx:1.25-alpine` as a lightweight, stable HTTP server that:\n531: - Responds to any path with 200\n532: - Has a small image footprint (fast Kind load)\n533: - Is publicly available (no registry auth needed)\n534: - Supports readiness probes via HTTP GET\n535: \n536: For picod auth tests, a minimal Go HTTP server image is built that:\n537: - Validates JWT tokens in Authorization header\n538: - Returns 200 for valid tokens, 401 for invalid\n539: - Is built from `cmd/picod` or a dedicated test image\n540: \n541: ### 5.8 Parallelization Strategy\n542: \n543: Tests run sequentially within each suite to avoid sandbox resource contention. Suites can run in parallel using Ginkgo's `--procs` flag if isolation is guaranteed:\n544: \n545: ```bash\n546: # Sequential (default, safe)\n547: go test ./test/e2e/... -v\n548: \n549: # Parallel (requires per-suite namespaces)\n550: go test ./test/e2e/... -v --ginkgo.procs=4\n551: ```\n552: \n553: Initial implementation uses sequential execution for simplicity and reliability. Parallelization can be added once the baseline is stable.\n554: \n555: ### 5.9 Pre-requisites\n556: \n557: | Requirement | Version | Check |\n558: |-------------|---------|-------|\n559: | Go | 1.23+ | `go version` |\n560: | Docker | 24+ | `docker version` |\n561: | Kind | v0.30.0 | `kind version` |\n562: | Helm | 3.12+ | `helm version` |\n563: | kubectl | 1.28+ | `kubectl version` |\n564: \n565: ### 5.10 Known Limitations\n566: \n567: 1. **No multi-node testing**: Kind single-node cluster; does not test cross-node networking.\n568: 2. **No TLS testing**: E2E runs without TLS; TLS-specific behavior tested in unit tests.\n569: 3. **No load testing**: E2E validates correctness, not performance. Load tests are separate.\n570: 4. **Image-dependent**: Tests require pre-built images; cannot test against arbitrary commits without building.\n571: 5. **Time-sensitive**: Idle cleanup tests depend on clock; may flake on slow CI runners. Mitigated by using short timeouts (1-2 minutes) in test fixtures.\n\n(End of file - total 571 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-041: E2E 集成测试 — Design\n\n## 1. Architecture\n\n### 1.1 Purpose\n\nThis AR covers end-to-end integration tests for the AgentCube system, validating the full request lifecycle across all four binaries (workloadmanager, router, agentd, picod) running in a real Kind Kubernetes cluster. Tests exercise CRD creation, sandbox lifecycle, reverse proxy routing, JWT authentication, session store synchronization, and idle cleanup.\n\n### 1.2 Scope\n\n| Component | Coverage | Test Type |\n|-----------|----------|-----------|\n| `test/e2e/` | Full system E2E | Kind cluster, real binaries, real CRDs |\n| `test/e2e/framework/` | Test framework utilities | Cluster setup, client helpers, assertions |\n| `test/e2e/suites/` | Test scenario groups | Sandbox lifecycle, proxy, auth, cleanup |\n| `test/e2e/fixtures/` | CRD YAML fixtures | AgentRuntime, CodeInterpreter manifests |\n| `Makefile` | `e2e`, `e2e-clean` targets | CI integration |\n\n### 1.3 System Context\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_alibaba-cn-qwen3.6-plus_20260410T073331Z/deployment/design-e2e.md","time":{"start":1775896085207,"end":1775896085214}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775896152967,"sessionID":"ses_2845c53fbffePPAJ9umtY57fu2","part":{"id":"prt_d7ba7c339001tFacAAJbU8BMlT","messageID":"msg_d7ba79c89001QpIimtBbtui87X","sessionID":"ses_2845c53fbffePPAJ9umtY57fu2","type":"tool","tool":"task","callID":"call_aa554da804b443aeabf9be78","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"description":"Find existing tasks.md patterns","prompt":"Search the changes/ directory for existing tasks.md files that are fully filled out (not TODO placeholders). Read 2-3 of the best examples to understand the task breakdown pattern, granularity, and format conventions used in this project. \n\nReturn:\n1. The file paths of 2-3 good examples\n2. The pattern/structure they follow\n3. How tasks are numbered and grouped\n4. How dependency graphs are structured\n5. Any conventions for task descriptions and acceptance criteria","subagent_type":"explore"},"output":"task_id: ses_284583501ffeLd9fWRrAv219fh (for resuming to continue this task if needed)\n\n<task_result>\nI have thoroughly analyzed multiple tasks.md files. Here is my complete report:\n\n---\n\n## 1. File Paths of 2-3 Good Examples\n\n| Example | File Path | Description |\n|---------|-----------|-------------|\n| **AR-040** | `/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_alibaba-cn-qwen3.6-plus_20260410T073331Z/changes/AR-040/tasks.md` | Python SDK/CLI testing -- 8 tasks, ~197 lines, very detailed test case specifications |\n| **AR-030** | `/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_alibaba-cn-qwen3.6-plus_20260410T073331Z/changes/AR-030/tasks.md` | Helm Chart templates -- 15 tasks (T-001 to T-015), ~322 lines, uses 3-digit numbering |\n| **AR-020** | `/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_alibaba-cn-qwen3.6-plus_20260410T073331Z/changes/AR-020/tasks.md` | CLI pack command -- 20 tasks (T1 to T20), ~606 lines, most comprehensive example |\n\nOther strong examples include AR-038 (Go workloadmanager tests, 18 tasks) and AR-039 (Go router/store/picod tests, 21 tasks).\n\n---\n\n## 2. Pattern/Structure They Follow\n\nEvery tasks.md file follows this consistent top-level structure:\n\n```markdown\n# AR-XXX: <Title> -- Tasks\n\n**Module:** <path> | **Language:** <lang> | **Size:** <S/M/L>\n**Base specs:** <source code paths>          (or \"Reference:\" for proposal/design links)\n**Precondition:** Stage ST-3 (Design) completed\n\n---\n\n## T-1: <Task Title>\n- [ ] <subtask description>\n- [ ] <subtask description>\n\n---\n\n## T-2: <Task Title>\n...\n\n---\n\n## Dependency Graph\n```\n<ASCII art dependency diagram>\n```\n\n## Parallelizable Groups\n| Group | Tasks | Prerequisites | Notes |\n|-------|-------|---------------|-------|\n\n## Coverage Targets Summary          (for test-focused tasks)\n| Subpackage | Target | Current | Gap |\n|------------|--------|---------|-----|\n\n## Acceptance Criteria              (in some files, e.g., AR-030, AR-020)\n| # | Criterion | Command |\n|---|-----------|---------|\n```\n\nKey structural conventions:\n- **Horizontal rules (`---`)** separate each task section.\n- **Checkbox lists (`- [ ]`)** are used for every subtask.\n- **Verification/Acceptance lines** appear at the end of each task section in bold, prefixed with `**Verification:**` or `**验收**:`.\n- The **Dependency Graph**, **Parallelizable Groups**, and **Coverage Targets Summary** sections always appear after all tasks.\n\n---\n\n## 3. How Tasks Are Numbered and Grouped\n\nThere are **three numbering conventions** observed across files:\n\n| Convention | Example | When Used |\n|------------|---------|-----------|\n| `T-1`, `T-2`, `T-3` | AR-040, AR-038, AR-039 | Most common; used in ~75% of files |\n| `T-001`, `T-002`, `T-003` | AR-030 | Used when tasks exceed 9 or for YAML/Helm work |\n| `T1`, `T2`, `T3` (no hyphen) | AR-020 | Used in earlier files; less common now |\n\n**Subtask numbering** follows the parent task number with a dot or space:\n- `1.1`, `1.2`, `1.3` (AR-020 style)\n- `T-001.01`, `T-001.02` (AR-030 style)\n\n**Grouping**: Tasks are grouped by logical concern or source file. For example:\n- AR-040: Each test file gets its own task (T-2 = test_code_interpreter.py, T-3 = test_data_plane.py, etc.)\n- AR-039: Each source file/submodule gets its own task (T-1 = backend.go, T-2 = errors.go, etc.)\n- AR-020: Each component/method gets its own task (T2 = MetadataOptions, T3 = AgentMetadata, T4 = MetadataService, etc.)\n\nThe final task is always a **verification gate** (e.g., \"Run full test suite and verify coverage\" or \"Code quality gates and final verification\").\n\n---\n\n## 4. How Dependency Graphs Are Structured\n\nDependency graphs use **ASCII art box-drawing characters** in fenced code blocks. Three patterns are used:\n\n**Pattern A -- Fan-in to a final task** (AR-040):\n```\nT-1 ──┬── T-2 ──┐\n      ├── T-3 ──┤\n      ├── T-4 ──┼── T-7 ── T-8\n      ├── T-5 ──┤\n      └── T-6 ──┘\n```\n\n**Pattern B -- All independent, converge to one** (AR-039):\n```\nT-1  ──┐\nT-2  ──┤\n...\nT-20 ──┘\n       │\n       ▼\n     T-21\n```\n\n**Pattern C -- Cascading pipeline** (AR-020):\n```\nT1 (项目脚手架) ───────────────────────┐\nT2 (MetadataOptions) ────────────────┐ │\nT3 (AgentMetadata 模型) ───────────┐ │ │\n...\nT16 (pack 编排) ←──────────────────┘ │ │\nT17 (CLI 命令入口) ←─────────────────┘ │\nT19 (E2E 集成测试) ←───────────────────┘\n     │\nT20 (质量门禁)\n```\n\n**Pattern D -- Multi-branch with annotations** (AR-038):\n```\nT-1 ──┬── T-2 ── T-4\n      │           │\n      └── T-3 ────┘\n\nT-5 ── (independent)\nT-9 ──┬── T-10\n      ├── T-11\n      └── T-12\n```\n\nThe **Parallelizable Groups** table always accompanies the graph, mapping groups (G1, G2, ...) to specific tasks with their prerequisites and notes.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Conventions for Task Descriptions and Acceptance Criteria\n\n### Task Titles\n- **Descriptive and specific**: `T-2: Extend test_code_interpreter.py -- CodeInterpreterClient gaps`\n- **File-level or component-level granularity**: Each task typically covers one source file, one test file, or one logical component.\n- **Language**: Titles are in English or Chinese depending on the author; both are acceptable.\n\n### Subtask Descriptions (checkbox items)\n- **Test tasks**: Each checkbox describes one test case with the test function name and expected behavior:\n  ```\n  - [ ] `test_stop_when_session_id_is_none` — session_id=None → skips delete_session, still closes dp and cp clients\n  ```\n- **Implementation tasks**: Each checkbox describes a specific implementation step:\n  ```\n  - [ ] 创建 `cmd/cli/agentcube/models/pack_models.py`\n  - [ ] 定义 `MetadataOptions` dataclass，字段与 design.md 表一致\n  ```\n- **Verification tasks**: Each checkbox is a concrete command to run:\n  ```\n  - [ ] `go test ./pkg/router/... -v` — all tests pass\n  - [ ] `go vet ./pkg/...` — no vet warnings\n  ```\n\n### Acceptance Criteria / Verification\nTwo patterns are used:\n\n**Inline per-task verification** (most common): At the end of each task section, a bold line specifies how to verify:\n```\n**Verification:** `pytest cmd/cli/tests/models/test_pack_models.py -v` 全部通过\n```\n```\n**验收**: `helm template test manifests/charts/base --include-crds | grep \"agentruntimes...\"` 有输出\n```\n\n**Global Acceptance Criteria table** (in larger tasks like AR-020, AR-030): A dedicated table at the end of the file:\n```markdown\n## Acceptance Criteria\n| # | Criterion | Command |\n|---|-----------|---------|\n| AC1 | pack 命令接受所有指定选项 | `kubectl-agentcube pack --help` 显示全部 9 个选项 |\n| AC2 | workspace 默认 `.` | `kubectl-agentcube pack` 使用当前目录 |\n...\n```\n\n### Coverage Targets Summary\nFor test-focused tasks, a table tracks coverage goals:\n```\n| Subpackage | Target | Current | Gap |\n|------------|--------|---------|-----|\n| `agentcube/code_interpreter.py` | >95% | 99% (1 line missing) | Fix 3 skipped stop tests + 16 new tests |\n```\n\n### Granularity Rules Observed\n- Tasks are sized so each can be completed in a single coding session (roughly 30min-2hrs).\n- Each task has **5-20 subtasks** (checkboxes).\n- Tasks are **independently testable** -- each has its own verification step.\n- The last task is always a **final verification gate** (run full test suite, check coverage, lint, etc.).\n</task_result>","metadata":{"sessionId":"ses_284583501ffeLd9fWRrAv219fh","model":{"modelID":"qwen3.6-plus","providerID":"alibaba-cn"},"truncated":false},"title":"Find existing tasks.md patterns","time":{"start":1775896087291,"end":1775896152964}}}}
